{{Infobox academic | name = Kim Fortun | birth_name = <!--unknown--> | birth_date = <!--unknown {{birth date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes}} For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{tl|birth year and age}} or a similar option.--> | birth_place = <!--unknown--> | nationality = American | occupation = Academic | discipline = [[Anthropologist]], [[science and technology studies]] scholar | spouse = Mike Fortun | alma_mater = Rice University<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kfortun.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/KFortunCV-7-27-2017.pdf|title=Kim Fortun Curriculum Vitae|last=Fortun|first=Kim|date=July 2017|website=kfortun.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> | workplaces = {{plainlist| * [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] (1993-2017) * [[University of California Irvine]] (2017-present)}} | boards = [[Society for Social Studies of Science]] | period = 1993-present | awards = Sharon Stephens Prize (2003) | title = Professor and Department Chair | main_interests = Environmental risk and disaster | notable_works = ''Advocacy After Bhopal'' | website = http://kfortun.org }}
'''Kim Fortun''', an American [[anthropologist]], is a professor and department chair at [[University of California Irvine]]'s department of anthropology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.anthropology.uci.edu/people/faculty.php|title=Core Faculty {{!}} Anthropology {{!}} UCI Social Sciences|website=www.anthropology.uci.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> Her interests extend also to [[science and technology studies]] with a focus on environmental risk and disaster.Since 2017, she has served as the president of the [[Society for Social Studies of Science|Society for Social Studies of Science (4S)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.4sonline.org/officers|title=-- The Society {{!}} Society for Social Studies of Science|website=www.4sonline.org|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref>
In 2003, Fortun's first book, ''Advocacy After Bhopal: Environmentalism, Disaster, New World Orders'', was awarded the Sharon Stephens Prize by the [[American Ethnological Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanethnologist.org/awards/sharon-stephens-prize|title=Sharon Stephens Prize {{!}} American Ethnological Society|website=American Ethnological Society|language=en|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> From 2005 to 2010, she edited the [[Cultural Anthropology (journal)|Journal of Cultural Anthropology]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kfortun.org/|title=Kim Fortun/|website=kfortun.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> Fortun currently helps lead multiple collaborative projects, including The Asthma Files and the Platform for Experimental and Collaborative Ethnography (PECE).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fortun|first=Kim |last2=Callahan|first2=Brian |last3=Costelloe-Kuehn|first3=Brandon |last4=Fidler|first4=Brad |last5=Kenner|first5=Alison |last6=Khandekar|first6=Aalok |last7=Morgan|first7=Alli |last8=Poirer|first8=Lindsay|last9=Fortun|first9=Mike|date=Forthcoming (2018)|title=Hosting the Platform for Experimental, Collaborative Ethnography|url=http://www.worldpece.org/content/fortun-kim-brian-callahan-brandon-costelloe-kuehn-brad-fidler-alison-kenner-aalok-khandekar|journal=HAU|volume=Special Issue|pages=|via=}}</ref>
